I don’t think it’s a stance against tfidf. It’s a great baseline and certainly my choice for candidate gen. However, based on the application (e.g. when there is a single source of truth) users may not be happy with it (especially given the web search experience is so great.)

I don't understand this stance against TF*IDF: TF*IDF is hard to beat at least as candidate generator. A combination of field-specific TF*IDF, including TF*IDF for proximity should make an extremely competitive system. In our TREC experiments, we were able to get about +50%.

It does go a long way for most people. More advanced is, of course, always an option, but often folks doing basic TF-IDF think they have to bite off the whole AI/ML thing, when there are often easy incremental wins to be had with simpler approaches and less investment

Modern archs include but not limited to out-of-box inverted index structure. ML for srch benefits from features emitted as a result of lucene matching/scoring. ML valuable in doc enrichment, query rewriting, learning weights for custom scoring funcs, reranking. Vespa?
I would assume basic clickstream is not enough, b/c session information would be quite useful for query reformulation and spell-checking.

You should check out @Lucidworks Fusion. We’ve been incorporating signals/ML into search to drive smarter ranking for 4+ years now. Basic clickstream models are almost always a big win and are simple to do. TF/IDF is important, but not the only factor.

Yep. In many @joostware consults and after sitting through various investment due diligence calls, I feel every company more or less accepts this status quo as a given or executes it poorly using some elasticsearch-like backend.

agreed. Based on my last 2 years at . @askspoke , my take on internal search is that while hard, a solid approach is to use innovative product flows to generate valuable signals. These signals + ML ranking techniques can do much better than plain old tfidf/elasticsearch.
